T1  - The impact of stochastic and deterministic trends on money–output causality: A multi-country investigation
AU  - Krol, Robert
AU  - Ohanian, Lee E.
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 45
IS  - 3
SP  - 291
EP  - 308
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/01/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(90)90001-A
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030440769090001A
AB  - This paper applies a statistical approach used by Stock and Watson (1989) in their study of U.S. money–output causality to analyze money–output relationships in five industrialized countries. In extending Stock and Watson's paper, we focus on whether money supply growth rates in our international sample seem to be characterized by deterministic time trends, and whether the practice of removing these trends sharpens statistical inference. We find evidence of deterministic trends in money supply growth in three of the five countries, but find that removin the time trends affects inference only in the U.S. sample. Moreover, the use of log-differenced data in two-, three-, and four-variable VARs in these countries provide very little information regarding macroeconomic relationships.
